  abstract = {National forests in the western United States are divided roughly in half between lands without roads managed for wilderness characteristics and lands with an extensive road system managed for multiple uses including resource extraction. We investigated the influence of these land use designations on fire ignitions, fire extent, and fire severity over the last three decades. Although roadless areas experienced fewer fire ignitions and are generally cooler, moister, and higher elevation landscapes less conducive to fire, there was a far greater extent of wildfire in these areas than in roaded landscapes managed for multiple uses. An area equivalent to approximately one-third of the roadless landscape burned in the last three decades, while an area equivalent to less than one-fifth of roaded lands experienced fire. Most of the largest fires that have burned on national forest land in recent years began in roadless areas. Whereas fire extent was greater in roadless areas, there was no significant difference in fire severity between roadless wilderness and areas with an extensive road system after accounting for biophysical differences between these areas. Although fire patterns in roadless areas may pose challenges to land managers, the available evidence suggests that the greater extent of fire in roadless areas may confer resilience to these landscapes in the face of climate change.},
